In any game, the point of rules is to provide for and to support fair play and general enjoyment for all involved. Pick a sport: if, in a game of that sport, a player goes outside the rules, other players, the referee, and sometimes the fans too bring the offending player or party back into line, whether through encouragement, enforcement authority innate to the referee’s position, or, in the case of fans, through booing or whistling aiming to embarrass. 
Minnesota statutes for elections have developed in length and complication since the first Minnesota Statutes were published in 1858, shortly after Minnesota joined the union of states. Here, at the beginning of 2026, the current 2025 statutes fill about 500 pages in a PDF document, which is a decrease of 36 pages from the 2023 version. (If including the MNSOS’s additional rules, there are more than 500 pages.)
The decrease from 2023 to 2025 is, for me, trending in the right direction—less is more—and I have throughout my last five years of thinking about this been able to reduce those 500 pages to a single page. That version (found in the Appendices), however, is only my ideal version. The goal of this book is to start a conversation among many, many thousands of Minnesotans. Last year, in 2025, I helped to send a three-page version of the statutes that I liked (written by someone else) to nearly every (if not every) legislator, to which there were exactly zero responses. 
Maybe the legislators want to hear from you; after all, it is you who has decided to read this and think about it at depth—up your game and they will likely up theirs. To have a productive conversation, we need something to look at. These rules can be looked at, even examined in depth, tracing the history of amendments, through the Minnesota Revisor’s website. Downloading the most recent 2023 and 2025 statutes is a start in surveying the rules of this game we call elections. I encourage you to read not only those sections where you feel comfortable (election judges will have experience with election day statutes, or IT specialists will be at home in the software-related sections), but also those areas where you have previously spent less effort or time.
One may further get a sense of the administrative side of elections by downloading the 2024 Election Judge Guide or the 2026 Combined Elections Calendar in .xlsx format here: https://www.sos.mn.gov/election-administration-campaigns/election-administration/election-calendars/ 
If one is interested in following current events (or examine previous proposed bills) in the Minnesota House or the Minnesota Senate, look for the Minnesota House Elections Finance and Government Operations Committee (meeting Mondays and Wednesdays, 1pm, in Capitol G23) and the Minnesota Senate Elections Committee (meeting Tuesdays and Thursdays at 3pm in Room 1200 Minnesota Senate Bldg)—both also have YouTube channels. Authored bills relating to elections would generally come before these committees before going to the full House or Senate. 
But from what framework shall we analyze them? 
